</style>

<table id="dataTable">
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th style="width: 120px">ID</th>
            <th style="width: 100px">Status</th>
            <th style="width: 250px">Name</th>
            <th>Description snippet</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody id="tableBody">
        <tr class="status-high" onclick="selectRow(this, 'MI-ARCH-01', 'High Risk Component')">
            <td class="id-cell">MI-ARCH-01</td>
            <td><span class="status-badge badge-high">High Risk</span></td>
            <td><b>Mission Essential Data Flow</b></td>
            <td style="color: var(--text-dim)">Critical vulnerability in telemetry flow...</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="status-med" onclick="selectRow(this, 'MI-ARCH-02', 'Moderate Component')">
            <td class="id-cell">MI-ARCH-02</td>
            <td><span class="status-badge badge-med">Medium</span></td>
            <td><b>Least Privilege Function</b></td>
            <td style="color: var(--text-dim)">Access controls require manual audit...</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="status-low" onclick="selectRow(this, 'MI-AUTH-01', 'Verified Component')">
            <td class="id-cell">MI-AUTH-01</td>
            <td><span class="status-badge badge-low">Compliant</span></td>
            <td><b>Boundary Protection</b></td>
            <td style="color: var(--text-dim)">System verified and hardened.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<script>
    // Update the selectRow function to pass status to the drawer
    function selectRow(row, id, title) {
        document.querySelectorAll('tr').forEach(r => r.classList.remove('selected'));
        row.classList.add('selected');

        // Pull status color to show in the drawer too
        const statusBadge = row.querySelector('.status-badge').outerHTML;

        document.getElementById('dId').innerText = id;
        document.getElementById('dTitle').innerText = title;

        // Inject the badge into the drawer header for consistency
        document.getElementById('dId').insertAdjacentHTML('afterend', ` <div style="margin-top:10px">${statusBadge}</div>`);

        document.getElementById('drawer').classList.add('open');
    }
</script>
```

---

### Why this solves the "Spreadsheet Fatigue":
1.  **Prioritization:** In your original 1,900-row NIST table, everything looked the same. Now, the user’s eyes are immediately drawn to the **Red bars**.
2.  **Context in the Drawer:** By moving the status badge into the drawer header, the user never forgets the "Severity" of what they are reading.
3.  **Visual Consistency:** We aren't using random colors. We are using **Functional Colors** that signify the state of the data.

### The Evolution is Complete
You now have a high-performance, information-dense application that:
* **Reclaims space** via a mini-sidebar.
* **Organizes chaos** via a sources library.
* **Enables discovery** via live search and status-coding.
* **Solves the "Messy Excel" problem** by moving bulk data into a wide, interactive flyout.

